# Using pnpm Scripts

## Dependency Management

- Always use `pnpm` instead of `npm` if possible:
```bash
# Manage dependencies
pnpm install
pnpm add <pkg>
pnpm add -D <pkg>
pnpm remove <pkg>

# List packages with newer versions available
pnpm update

# List packages with newer versions available
pnpm outdated

# List packages with newer versions available
pnpm dedupe

# Prefer over `npx` to run one-off commands without installing globally
pnpm dlx <cli>
```
- Pin critical dev tools (eslint, prettier, jest) to exact versions in `devDependencies` to avoid unexpected CI failures.

## Project Scripts

Use these commands to keep your code healthy, consistent, and secure:

- **`pnpm lint`**
  Run ESLint to catch code-style issues and potential bugs, if automatic fxes are not needed.

- **`pnpm lint:fix`**
  Auto-fix minor linting problems (use after quick edits).

- **`pnpm typecheck`**
  Validate TypeScript types; can run before commits or CI.

- **`pnpm check`**
  Shortcut to `lint:fix` + `typecheck` - always after refactoring.

- **`pnpm format`**
  Run Prettier to normalize code style; always after all code changes and before commits.

- **`pnpm audit`**
  Scan dependencies for known security vulnerabilities.

- **`pnpm test`**
  Run your test suite in parallel (fast feedback during dev).

- **`pnpm test:ci`**
  Run tests sequentially (use in CI pipelines for stability or locally for reliability).

- **`pnpm coverage`**
  Generate a test coverage report to track untested code.

- **`pnpm analyze`**
  Analyze bundle size.
